trans-unit.source: Applies To: Azure AD Graph API
trans-unit.target: Applies To: Azure AD Graph API

trans-unit.source: The Azure AD Reports and Events REST API Preview provides read-only access to the access and usage reporting data maintained within an Azure AD tenant.
trans-unit.target: The Azure AD Reports and Events REST API Preview provides read-only access to the access and usage reporting data maintained within an Azure AD tenant.

trans-unit.source: Please refer to the article <externalLink><linkText>View your access and usage reports</linkText><linkUri>http://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/documentation/articles/active-directory-view-access-usage-reports/</linkUri></externalLink> for an overview of the available report types, and information on accessing the reporting feature in the related Azure Management Portal user interface.
trans-unit.target: Please refer to the article <externalLink><linkText>View your access and usage reports</linkText><linkUri>http://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/documentation/articles/active-directory-view-access-usage-reports/</linkUri></externalLink> for an overview of the available report types, and information on accessing the reporting feature in the related Azure Management Portal user interface.

trans-unit.source: Familiarity with Azure AD authentication and application configuration is also necessary before using the Reports and Events API Preview.
trans-unit.target: Familiarity with Azure AD authentication and application configuration is also necessary before using the Reports and Events API Preview.

trans-unit.source: If you are unfamiliar with the concepts associated with Azure AD authentication, and/or the ability to grant permissions to an application to allow access to your tenant, please review the <externalLink><linkText>Authentication Scenarios for Azure AD</linkText><linkUri>http://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/documentation/articles/active-directory-authentication-scenarios/</linkUri></externalLink> article, and specifically the section titled <externalLink><linkText>Basics of Registering an Application in Azure AD</linkText><linkUri>http://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/documentation/articles/active-directory-authentication-scenarios/#basics-of-registering-an-application-in-azure-ad</linkUri></externalLink>.
trans-unit.target: If you are unfamiliar with the concepts associated with Azure AD authentication, and/or the ability to grant permissions to an application to allow access to your tenant, please review the <externalLink><linkText>Authentication Scenarios for Azure AD</linkText><linkUri>http://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/documentation/articles/active-directory-authentication-scenarios/</linkUri></externalLink> article, and specifically the section titled <externalLink><linkText>Basics of Registering an Application in Azure AD</linkText><linkUri>http://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/documentation/articles/active-directory-authentication-scenarios/#basics-of-registering-an-application-in-azure-ad</linkUri></externalLink>.

trans-unit.source: The latter section also links to a more detailed <legacyLink xlink:href="b08d91fa-6a64-4deb-92f4-f5857add9ed8" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Adding, Updating, and Removing an Application</legacyLink> article, including specific permissions for Accessing the Graph API, once you are ready to configure access for your application.
trans-unit.target: The latter section also links to a more detailed <legacyLink xlink:href="b08d91fa-6a64-4deb-92f4-f5857add9ed8" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Adding, Updating, and Removing an Application</legacyLink> article, including specific permissions for Accessing the Graph API, once you are ready to configure access for your application.

trans-unit.source: Finally, you will need access to an Azure AD tenant once you are ready to configure access for your application.
trans-unit.target: Finally, you will need access to an Azure AD tenant once you are ready to configure access for your application.

trans-unit.source: Please refer to the <link xlink:href="18f51652-161d-4a3b-b25d-fd979a9dea54" DisplayType="title" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Azure AD Graph API Prerequisites</link> article in the Graph API documentation for more details and related code samples.
trans-unit.target: Please refer to the <link xlink:href="18f51652-161d-4a3b-b25d-fd979a9dea54" DisplayType="title" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Azure AD Graph API Prerequisites</link> article in the Graph API documentation for more details and related code samples.

trans-unit.source: You can find a companion ASP.NET sample app called <externalLink><linkText>WebApp-GraphAPI-Reporting</linkText><linkUri>https://github.com/AzureADSamples/WebApp-GraphAPI-Reporting</linkUri></externalLink> on Github with step-by-step instructions in readme.md, as well as an overview of all samples that illustrate usage of the Active Directory Authentication Library (ADAL) and the Graph API from multiple platforms on the main <externalLink><linkText>Azure AD Code Samples</linkText><linkUri>http://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/documentation/articles/active-directory-code-samples/</linkUri></externalLink> page.

trans-unit.source: Once you have your tenant configured and are ready to access the Reports and Events API, refer to the <link xlink:href="8760e164-b6ee-43f5-b0c2-0d8737356c6d" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Quickstart for the Azure AD Graph API</link> article for details on the basics of constructing a service URL, HTTP request header, and related OData access token, as well as information on using testing tools (ie: Graph Explorer, Fiddler) to run test requests against your tenant.
trans-unit.target: Once you have your tenant configured and are ready to access the Reports and Events API, refer to the <link xlink:href="8760e164-b6ee-43f5-b0c2-0d8737356c6d" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Quickstart for the Azure AD Graph API</link> article for details on the basics of constructing a service URL, HTTP request header, and related OData access token, as well as information on using testing tools (ie: Graph Explorer, Fiddler) to run test requests against your tenant.

trans-unit.source: Keeping in mind that all Reports and Events operations are addressed using the following OData compliant URL format, where <codeInline>tenant-name</codeInline> is the name of your Azure AD tenant, and <codeInline>reports/%%amp;lt;service-operation%%amp;gt;</codeInline> is the path to the specific report resource you want to call: <codeInline>https://graph.windows.net/%%amp;lt;tenant-name%%amp;gt;/reports/%%amp;lt;service-operation%%amp;gt;?api-version=beta</codeInline>.
trans-unit.target: Keeping in mind that all Reports and Events operations are addressed using the following OData compliant URL format, where <codeInline>tenant-name</codeInline> is the name of your Azure AD tenant, and <codeInline>reports/%%amp;lt;service-operation%%amp;gt;</codeInline> is the path to the specific report resource you want to call: <codeInline>https://graph.windows.net/%%amp;lt;tenant-name%%amp;gt;/reports/%%amp;lt;service-operation%%amp;gt;?api-version=beta</codeInline>.

trans-unit.source: Also, the Reports and Events API supports a subset of the OData Query Options supported by the main Graph API (see next section).
trans-unit.target: Also, the Reports and Events API supports a subset of the OData Query Options supported by the main Graph API (see next section).

trans-unit.source: The following restrictions apply to filter expressions:
trans-unit.target: The following restrictions apply to filter expressions:

trans-unit.source: All reports default to the prior 30 days of history.
trans-unit.target: All reports default to the prior 30 days of history.

trans-unit.source: Not all properties of supported entities can be used in a filter expression.
trans-unit.target: Not all properties of supported entities can be used in a filter expression.

trans-unit.source: See the property details for each of the Reports and Events entities below in this topic for more information.
trans-unit.target: See the property details for each of the Reports and Events entities below in this topic for more information.

trans-unit.source: For example: <parameterReference>https://graph.windows.net/%%amp;lt;tenant-name%%amp;gt;/reports/audit/?api-version=beta%%amp;amp;$filter=(eventTime gt 2014-03-01 and eventTime lt 2015-04-23) or eventTime lt 2015-02-01</parameterReference>
trans-unit.target: For example: <parameterReference>https://graph.windows.net/%%amp;lt;tenant-name%%amp;gt;/reports/audit/?api-version=beta%%amp;amp;$filter=(eventTime gt 2014-03-01 and eventTime lt 2015-04-23) or eventTime lt 2015-02-01</parameterReference>

trans-unit.source: Comparison operators: <languageKeyword>eq</languageKeyword> (equal to), <languageKeyword>gt</languageKeyword> (greater than), <languageKeyword>ge</languageKeyword> (greater than or equal to), <languageKeyword>lt</languageKeyword> (less than), and <languageKeyword>le</languageKeyword> (less than or equal to) are supported.
trans-unit.target: Comparison operators: <languageKeyword>eq</languageKeyword> (equal to), <languageKeyword>gt</languageKeyword> (greater than), <languageKeyword>ge</languageKeyword> (greater than or equal to), <languageKeyword>lt</languageKeyword> (less than), and <languageKeyword>le</languageKeyword> (less than or equal to) are supported.

trans-unit.source: <languageKeyword>null</languageKeyword> values are not supported as an operand in filter expressions.
trans-unit.target: <languageKeyword>null</languageKeyword> values are not supported as an operand in filter expressions.

trans-unit.source: Spaces in the query string should be URL-encoded before sending a request.
trans-unit.target: Spaces in the query string should be URL-encoded before sending a request.

trans-unit.source: For example, the following query string, <codeInline>https://graph.windows.net/%%amp;lt;tenant-name%%amp;gt;/reports/audit/?api-version=beta%%amp;amp;$filter=eventTime gt 2014-03-01 and eventTime lt 2015-04-23</codeInline>, should be URL encoded as: <codeInline>https://graph.windows.net/%%amp;lt;tenant-name%%amp;gt;/reports/audit/?api-version=beta%%amp;amp;$filter=eventTime%20gt%202014-03-01%20and%20eventTime%20lt%202015-04-23</codeInline>.
trans-unit.target: For example, the following query string, <codeInline>https://graph.windows.net/%%amp;lt;tenant-name%%amp;gt;/reports/audit/?api-version=beta%%amp;amp;$filter=eventTime gt 2014-03-01 and eventTime lt 2015-04-23</codeInline>, should be URL encoded as: <codeInline>https://graph.windows.net/%%amp;lt;tenant-name%%amp;gt;/reports/audit/?api-version=beta%%amp;amp;$filter=eventTime%20gt%202014-03-01%20and%20eventTime%20lt%202015-04-23</codeInline>.

trans-unit.source: Service Metadata, Entities, Properties, and Operations
trans-unit.target: Service Metadata, Entities, Properties, and Operations

trans-unit.source: All entities and properties supported by the Reports and Events OData resources are specified in its Service Metadata Document, which defines the service’s Entity Data Model (EDM) using standard OData Common Schema Definition Language (CSDL).
trans-unit.target: All entities and properties supported by the Reports and Events OData resources are specified in its Service Metadata Document, which defines the service’s Entity Data Model (EDM) using standard OData Common Schema Definition Language (CSDL).

trans-unit.source: You can retrieve the CSDL metadata by adding the $metadata segment to the /reports resource path in the URL: <codeInline>https://graph.windows.net/%%amp;lt;tenant-name%%amp;gt;/reports/$metadata?api-version=beta</codeInline>.
trans-unit.target: You can retrieve the CSDL metadata by adding the $metadata segment to the /reports resource path in the URL: <codeInline>https://graph.windows.net/%%amp;lt;tenant-name%%amp;gt;/reports/$metadata?api-version=beta</codeInline>.

trans-unit.source: Excluding the $metadata segment will return a list of the available report resources as JSON data in the response body.
trans-unit.target: Excluding the $metadata segment will return a list of the available report resources as JSON data in the response body.

trans-unit.source: The OData Service Operations that can be used in the resource path to access the event data collections, are defined by the “Name” attribute of the <EntitySet> elements near the bottom of the CSDL.
trans-unit.target: The OData Service Operations that can be used in the resource path to access the event data collections, are defined by the “Name” attribute of the <EntitySet> elements near the bottom of the CSDL.

trans-unit.source: For example, to access the event data collection associated with the “audit” report, you would use a URL similar to the following: <codeInline>https://graph.windows.net/%%amp;lt;tenant-name%%amp;gt;/reports/auditEvents?api-version=beta</codeInline>.
trans-unit.target: For example, to access the event data collection associated with the “audit” report, you would use a URL similar to the following: <codeInline>https://graph.windows.net/%%amp;lt;tenant-name%%amp;gt;/reports/auditEvents?api-version=beta</codeInline>.

trans-unit.source: The namespace that defines the OData entities supported by the Reports and Events API is Microsoft.ActiveDirectory.DataService.PublicApi.Model.Reporting, which is different from the one that defines the entities in the main Graph API, which is Microsoft.DirectoryServices.
trans-unit.target: The namespace that defines the OData entities supported by the Reports and Events API is Microsoft.ActiveDirectory.DataService.PublicApi.Model.Reporting, which is different from the one that defines the entities in the main Graph API, which is Microsoft.DirectoryServices.
